@jamestewartjr  What if we make a job prep goal? The artifact would be a completed resume, and we can get together and do mock interview with questions from Hacking the Coding interview... and give each other reviews on the mock interview and our resumes.
we could also set a spec to reach out via email to at least one contact from networking or apply for one job a day?

@jamestewartjr 1) us getting jobs is crucial to LG being successful so it seems like they should give us time to pursue that. 2) Learners Guild said they would have us technically ready to get a job by then end of this program. Part of that process is practicing whiteboarding, interviewing....being able to translate your technical skills to employers. 3) Bootcamps normally have their students do a final project and then they have companies that the schools work with come and watch them present their final projects...and they do other job hunting networking events worked into their program. Learners Guild said they wouldn't do any marketing or work with particular companies and that sort of makes sense to me...it's all for show and it hasn't been helping a lot of these people from bootcamps get jobs lately. "Marketing" only goes so far...some people are getting job interviews here that have no social media presence or go to popular networking events. Learners Guild has said that we can take whatever time off that we need to go to interviews and to practice interviewing so I don't see why we can't spend a week getting our job hunt and resumes together, figure out what companies we want to apply for and practicing interviewing.

I see what you mean, though about making a goal "to job hunt" and then have a bunch of people that still have months left here wanting to do that goal now when it doesn't make sense. I don't know the answer, there are only so many hours in the day and job hunting takes time. A lot of people can't afford to live without the stipend so they have to find the time to job hunt at some point. People here have been taking the agency to practice whiteboarding here on the weekends and normally post about it in echo...I guess I'm wondering what other strategies you are looking for @jamestewartjr ?

Great questions @shakalee14: feel free to link me to any job descriptions of the types of roles you're targeting. Junior dev interviews are definitely *not* the same: some weigh more heavily on practical skills/coding ability, some ask questions about topics you'd learn in a data structures and/or algorithms course (e.g., "How would you detect and remove a loop from a linked list?"), others rely on trivia about programming languages (e.g., "How does 'virtual' work in C++?", "What are the differences between a class and an interface?")(though this, thankfully, has become less common), some focus on object oriented design ("Design Monopoly"), some focus on systems design (e.g., "Design Twitter"), etc.
I also highly recommend doing this after you have a solid idea of how to implement the basic data structures and algorithms described in the core goals (#128 and #123).

I'm having a huge tension about the LG weekly process vs the iterative improvement process that's needed to get a job. I'm very hesitant to request a goal because it would create this impulsive action among "the rest" to see if they are "job ready" what ever that means. Many thousands of less skilled people have gotten jobs. Plus, getting jobs goals are different from learning stuff goals so those of us not in a level with mostly July cohort would have team tensions. There is an argument that interviewing for a job is not the goal of LG; therefore, should be kept outside of guild hours. I would argue to that statement with - learning to present oneself well (confidently answer difficult questions, present a cohesive-compelling story, and sharing your knowledge) are skills of career "moving" developers. None of the current weekly goals allow for such a process. Plus, what would be an artifact: updated resume, increasing LinkedIn views, job offer?  Ultimately my question is: what strategies and tactics (SATs) are you, learners, using to stay engaged with the game AND meeting your personal job search goals. If you want to share gray hat SATs with me because they are :eye: :eye: . You know how to contact me. Have a great weekend!
https://media.giphy.com/media/136V8raQQogOfm/giphy.gif

As I said before, I don't believe a goal is a proper solution even if it is a solo goal. Maybe that's the best solution: whiteboard 25 questions, do 7 informational interviews etc... If it is, I feel bad that the only agency people have is to make goals related to the matrix. The goal library in its current form has created it's own problems: the specs are now immutable; therefore, guildies are less likely to debate trade-offs therefore less likely to have the "I have strong opinions, but loosely held" POV.

I really believe a goal is a bad fit.The goal library in its current form has a structure of do these things for a week, nothing else: specs are set, articles are preset, end result is much more structured then we created in our early days. Maybe I don't understand the job search process, but it has been a lot more dynamic, a lot more personal, and a lot less structured. I'm marketing myself, my skills, and my ability to be a fit for a company. LG has specifically said they will not be doing the marketing for us. The job search process is not compatible to the LG system. Thoughts @Anasauce ?

Hey friends - I have a little experiment I'd like to invite 2 or 3 of you into joining. We were planning to work with Launch Code to support learners in their job search. However, I've learned that Launch Code is somewhat limited in their scope because of where they're located. They're based in St. Louis and have offices in Miami, Rhode Island, and the Pacific Northwest. As a result they predominantly place applicants in companies located in those cities. They have limited relationships with companies in SF/Bay Area, New York and Chicago though they have placed some folks in companies there, but with much less frequency. 

That being said, Launch Code does have resources that can be very useful to all of you at this point in your ramp up to interviews. Here's the process: You apply to their program, take their tech assessments (coding puzzles) and interview with them. Then you'll get feedback on where you can tighten up your skills and interviewing presentation. 

The objective is for you to get another set of eyes on your work in addition to the support our SEPs are providing. So far, Nico, Monica and Ana are gonna participate. Got room for 2 or 3 more of you. Let me know if you're interested and I'll get you all set up. <3

what up July lovelies. Do you have a job search accountability buddy yet? you know, someone who knows where you're applying and when your interviews are? someone who holds you accountable to prep work and who tells you when something is misspelled on your linkedin profile? someone who reminds you of how awesome you are when your superego is doing the most? if  you don't have at least one of these people in your corner, then hurry up and get one. 

if you've found an awesome recruiter, share the resource. recruiters get paid by the companies they place you at (just in case you didn't know) so they have a vested interest in getting you a job. you don't need to do the job search on your own. buddy up. talk to Stephanie. talk to your learning facilitator. talk to your favorite SEP. 

that is all. love you all. <3
